Pendulum Continued
==================
	mry''+mgsin(y)=x(t)

	System is not linear

	To make it linear, approximate sin(y) = y

	mry''+ mgsiny=x(t)

	x(t)=e^(iwt)
	y(t)=H(w)e^(iwt)

	mr(H(w)e^(iwt))''+mgH(w)e^(iwt)=e^(iwt)

	mrH(w)(e^(iwt))''+mgH(w)e^(iwt)=e^(iwt)
	mrH(w)(iw)^2(e^(iwt))+mgH(w)e^(iwt)=e^(iwt)
	mrH(w)(iw)^2+mgH(w)=1
	H(w)(mr(-(w)^2)+mg)=1
	H(w)=1/(mg-mr(w)^2)
	H(w)=1/(m(g-r(w)^2))

	H(w) is asymptotic at sqrt(g/r), the resonant frequency

	Is the magnitude of the frequency response always an even function?
	-------------------------------------------------------------------
		H(w) = a_1 e^(iwT_1) + a_2 e^(iwT_2)
		H(w) = a_1 e^(-iwT_1) + a_2 e^(-iwT_2)
		H(-w)=H*(w)
		
		e^(iwt)--->LTI-->y1(t)
		e^(-iwt)-->LTI-->y2(t)

		y2(t)=y1*(t)
		(H(w)e^(iwt))*=(H(-w)e^(-iwt)) -- Complex Conjugate Symmetry

		In engineering, system is always real.

		b=a*
		=>|b|=|a|
		So the magnitude of the frequency response is always even.
		\angle H(-w)=-\angle H(w)
		So the phase of the frequency response is always odd.
	

	Differentiation
	---------------
		x(t)-->d/(dt)-->y(t)

		Both linear and time invariant.

		H(w)=iw=>|H(w)|=|w|
	
	Integration
	-----------
		x(t)-->Integral-->y(t)

		y(t)=1/T \integral_(t-T)^t x(s)ds, average over a window

		x(t)=e^(it)


		y(t)=1/T \integral_(t-T)^t e^(iws)ds
		=(e^(iws))/(iwT) from t-T to t
		=(e^(iwt)-e^(iw(t-T)))/(iwT)
		=(e^(iwt))(1-e^(-iwT))/(iwT)=(e^(iwt))H(w)
		=>H(w)=(1-e^(-iwT))
		|H(w)=1/(wT) sqrt(2(i-cos(wt)))

		w is large=> H(w) -> 0
		w is small=> H(w) -> 1

		Problem when w=0

		H(w) ~ 1/(sqrt(wT)) -> infinity
